# Element Model Conventions

## Core Types

- All shapes extend `ExcalidrawElement` (defined in `packages/excalidraw/types.ts`).
- Specializations: `ExcalidrawLinearElement` (arrows, lines), `ExcalidrawTextElement`, `ExcalidrawImageElement`, etc.
- Every element has: `id` (nanoid string), `version` (incremented on each mutation), `seed` (Rough.js determinism), `versionNonce`.

## Mutating Elements

- NEVER mutate element objects directly — always use `scene.mutateElement(element, updates)`.
- Direct property assignment (`element.x = 10`) bypasses version tracking and breaks undo history.
- For bulk mutations, collect updates and apply them in a single `mutateElement` call.

## Accessing Elements

- Read elements from the scene via `scene.getNonDeletedElementsMap()` or `scene.getNonDeletedElements()`.
- Do NOT hold stale references to element objects across async boundaries — re-read from the scene.
- Deleted elements remain in the array with `isDeleted: true`; filter them out unless you specifically need history.

## Bindings and Arrows

- Arrow-to-element binding is managed by the binding system in `packages/element/src/binding.ts`.
- Do NOT directly set `startBinding` / `endBinding` on linear elements — use the binding API.
- When moving bound elements, update arrow bindings via `updateBoundElements(...)`.

## IDs and Ordering

- Generate element IDs with `nanoid()` from `packages/common`.
- Element z-order is determined by array position — first element is bottom, last is top.
- Fractional indexing (`packages/excalidraw/fractionalIndex.ts`) is used for ordering in collaboration.

## How to verify

- `yarn test:typecheck` — ensures element type contracts are satisfied.
- `yarn test` — run unit tests including element mutation tests in `packages/excalidraw/__tests__/`.
- Manually smoke-test: create, move, group, and delete shapes; confirm undo/redo works correctly after any element-layer change.
